  "theory": {
    "explanation": "Present Perfect tense\n\nForm: have / has + past participle (3rd form of the verb)\n\nWhen we use it:\n  • Life experience (ever, never): \"Have you ever been abroad?\"\n  • Actions just completed (just, already): \"I've just finished.\"\n  • A result visible now: \"She has lost her keys.\" (she still doesn't have them)\n  • Duration up to now (for, since): \"I've lived here for ten years.\"\n\nPatterns:\n  Affirmative: I/You/We/They have + pp    |  He/She/It has + pp\n  Negative:    haven't + pp               |  hasn't + pp\n  Questions:   Have + subject + pp?     |  Has + subject + pp?",
    "examples": [
      {
        "sentence": "I have seen this film before.",
        "explanation": "Affirmative: I + have + seen (pp of 'see'). Describes past experience."
      },
      {
        "sentence": "She hasn't cooked dinner yet.",
        "explanation": "Negative: she + hasn't + cooked (pp of 'cook'). Yet = not yet — at the end."
      },
      {
        "sentence": "Have they ever been to London?",
        "explanation": "Question: Have + they + been (pp of 'go/be'). Ever = at any time — after have/has."
      }
    ]
  }
